Incident.Summary: The suspect was placed under arrest for driving under the influence of alcohol, possession of CDS not cannabis, and Cannabis over the civil amount. The suspect was also carrying a handgun while impaired.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
This incident was captured on in-car camera (T-30)/body worn camera

Defendant: Jorelle Freeman
Virginia Soundex: F-655-439-005-007
Date of Birth: 01/02/1991
Date of arrest: 01/07/2023
Time of arrest: 0208
DUI # 23-001
Scene Processing:
     The handgun, suspected CDS not cannabis, suspected cannabis were seized and captured on Maryland State Police Property Records and Maryland State Police Chain of Custody Logs (MSP Form 067). The suspect was read his Miranda Rights from a Maryland State Police Advise of Miranda Rights Form (MSP Form 180).

CERTIFICATE AND TRAINING
  • Trained in administering Standardized Field Sobriety Tests through the Maryland State Police and National Highway Safety Administration.
  •  Advanced Roadside Impaired Driving Enforcement School.

VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1):
     On 01/07/2023 at approximately 0154 hours, Tpr. Richards and I were southbound on Three Notch Road (MD RT 235) in the area of South Hampton Drive, Lexington Park, St. Mary's County, Maryland, 20653. While traveling southbound, I was behind a gold 2005 Chevrolet Tahoe bearing Maryland registration A306432. While behind the vehicle, I observed it swerve out of its lane of travel four (4) separate times. The vehicle swerved three times out of lane # 2 onto the shoulder before abruptly correcting the swerve and re entering the lane. The vehicle then swerved a fourth time out of lane #2 into lane #1 before abruptly correcting its swerve and reentering its lane. I activated my emergency equipment to conduct a traffic stop on the vehicle. The vehicle pulled slowly onto the shoulder before coming to a stop. I then made contact with the driver and sole occupant of the vehicle who was identified by his Maryland driver's license as Jorelle Freeman (B/M DOB: 01/02/1991). 
PERSONAL CONTACT (PHASE 2):
   Upon initial contact with Mr. Freeman, I detected the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from his breath. While speaking with Mr. Freeman, I observed his eyes to be droopy and bloodshot, his speech to be slurred, his movements to be slow, and he appeared confused, being unable to initially find his registration card. When asked how many alcoholic beverages he had this evening, Mr. Freeman advised he had a few "beers." I asked Mr. Freeman to exit the vehicle to perform Standardized Field Sobriety Tests (SFST's). Mr. Freeman had to be asked several times to exit his vehicle before complying.

PRE-ARREST SCREENING PHASE:
    Prior to performing SFST's, I deactivated my front facing emergency equipment. Prior to administering the SFST's, I asked Mr. Freeman if he took any drugs of medication, which he advised he did not. I asked Mr. Freeman if he could walk a straight line or lift his leg up off the ground and he advised he could. I asked Mr. Freeman if he had any injuries which he advised his right knee was injured and was previously dislocated. Mr. Freeman was wearing glasses at the time and refused to take them off to perform the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus. While speaking with Mr. Freeman outside of the vehicle, I continued to detect the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from his breath.

HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS (6/6 clues observed)
The first test given was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus Test. The tip of my pen was used as the test’s stimulus and was held approximately 12 inches away from Mr. Freemans's eyes. Mr. Freeman was instructed to look straight ahead, keeping his head still while following and focusing on the tip of the pen with his eyes until told to stop. Mr. Freeman's pupils were equal in size and they had equal tracking, and had no sign of resting nystagmus. Mr. Freeman was asked if he understood the instruction that was given to him which he stated ''Yes." 
1. Lack of smooth pursuit: Present in both eyes.
2. Distinct and sustained nystagmus at maximum deviation: Present in both eyes.
3. Onset of nystagmus prior to 45 degrees: Present in both eyes.

WALK AND TURN: Refused
ONE LEG STAND: Refused
PRELIMINARY BREATH TEST: Mr. Freeman REFUSED the preliminary breath test. 
    
     Prior to completing the Walk and Turn and One Leg stand, Mr. Freeman advised he had passed the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus, and due to that reason, I could not legally ask him to complete any of the other tests. Mr. Freeman refused to complete the Walk and Turn and One Leg stand, as well as refused to take a Preliminary Breath Test (PBT).

ARREST:
    Based on the following, I had reason to believe Mr. Freeman was operating a motor vehicle under the influence of alcohol:
Droopy, bloodshot eyes,
Inability to follow directions,
Detected the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from his breath,
Admission to consuming alcohol
Movements to be slow and deliberate,
Observations during Standardized Field Sobriety Tests.

     Mr. Freeman was placed under arrest at approximately 0208 hours. While conducting a search incident to arrest of Mr. Freeman, I located a plastic baggie in his back right pocket containing four small blue pills individually wrapped in plastic. I contacted the Maryland Poison Control Center which identified the pills as Oxycodone, a schedule two drug. Upon conducting a search incident to arrest of the vehicle, upon opening the driver's side door, I located two (2) plastic bags containing suspected cannabis in the driver's side door compartment.  Located in a holster attached to the underside of the steering wheel column was a Springfield 9mm pistol. The pistol was loaded however a round was not in the chamber. The firearm was registered to Mr. Freeman, who had a valid concealed carry permit which was located in his vehicle. While conducting the search of the vehicle in the rear passenger seat was a backpack/cooler. Upon opening the backpack/cooler, I located a black plastic bag, in which was a large plastic bag containing suspected cannabis, and several smaller bags of suspected cannabis. The total weight of suspected cannabis located inside of the vehicle is approximately 469.8 grams. Cannabis is a schedule one drug.
    
     Mr. Freeman was subsequently transported to the Maryland State Police Leonardtown Barrack and at 0403 hours consented to take the Intoximeter test. Mr. Freeman gave a breath sample of 0.15 BrAC. The Maryland Gun Center was contacted referencing the firearm and Investigator Barclay advised to charge Mr. Freeman with carrying, wearing, or transporting a handgun while under the influence of alcohol or drugs. Mr. Freeman was subsequently transported to the St. Mary's County Detention Center and charged with DUI, CDS possession not cannabis, possession of cannabis greater than civil amount, and handgun wear/carry while under the influence of alcohol. Mr. Freeman was given copies of all paperwork.

Case Closed by Arrest.

All events occurred in St. Mary's County, Maryland.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: On Wednesday, January 11, 2023 at approximately 1300 hours, I, D/Sgt. Linger #3143, test fired the weapon seized in this investigation.  The test fire occurred at the Leonardtown Barrack in the presence of S/T S. Ditoto #5416.  The gun was operable and capable of being fired.  The test shots have been forwarded to the Maryland State Police Firearm/Toolmark Unit for entry and/or storage in the National Integrated Ballistic Information Network (NIBIN).

Scene Processing:
      I received one (1) NIBIN report, which is attached to this report.

Physical Evidence:
One (1) NIBIN report.

Narrative:
     On 02/10/2023 at approximately 0602 hours, I received a NIBIN memo referencing the seized firearm. The firearm was test fired and no NIBIN investigative lead was developed. A copy of the NIBIN report is attached to this report.
